Text
Greetings, Brothers and Sisters of the Champions.

Please consider this note writ on the behalf of Xor and myself. I write on an
occurrance that happened during Xor and my mission to feed and clothe the hungry 
and needy within Bandor, Earendam, and Gaald
from which we have recently returned.

I write of the visions.


From what we understand, Ealiryon, Brachaormaul, Malusmi, and Ralisaren have had these
dreams. Brachaormaul's happened while he was in a place of great darkness, which might
be a clue as to their meanings. All of the visions included the feeling of an unseen
presence fading into view from the blackness, oft in the form of a blindingly radiant
light.  As much as Xor wants to believe that this may be an ascent for him, I highly
doubt this. *here there is an illegible smudge, probably caused by a quick jerk of the
writer's arm*


At the same time, I also wonder how certain conclusions on the meaning of the visions
have been reached. Ralisaren seemed intent on stating that it was a portend of war, but
how this was come to, I cannot comprehend. None of the visions, as far as I know, 
incorporated violence or anger or destruction. Only peace and light. Perhaps this speaks
to the temperament of Ralisaren himself.
Brachaormaul offered that they may signify a long hard road on which all of the walkers
of the Light must toil to come to a greater reward. This, too, seems like an odd 
conclusion, considering that there was little toil or hardship given to the light as it
shone through the darkness. The stories from my bretheren Malusmi and Ealiryon, have we
yet to hear, as we have not had the opportunity to talk with either of them since we
returned.


After long periods of thinking on the subject, Xor and I believe that the idea that the
light signifies a new Divine Presence on the side of the Truth and the Light is most likely
the best answer at this juncture.  No other idea addresses the fact that all visions
felt a new, unseen presence. We do not believe that these visions are something to fear
or try to hide from, but rather something to embrace and eagerly await further actions by
our Great God, Lord Jolinn, or any of His compatriots.


Please, all of you, do write to Xor and me of your thoughts on this scroll, or speak
to us on it in person.  We believe that this issue is of great importance to the Champions,
and the entire land of Avendar as a whole.


Thank you for reading,
Pfusch.
~
