Dearest Brachaormaul,

I understand your concern in the issue of the Axe and wish to offer
greater depth of detail in how the axe came to me and what its
purpose in my hands was.

A few weeks past, Bastahvilist had the axe himself. How he came upon
it, I do not know, but he seemed to have had it for years. One day, he
was attacked and the axe was thieved from his body by some shadow-dwelling
being.  Eventually, the axe worked its way back to its rightful owner, 
Sir Melaith.

Bastahvilist went to retrieve the axe, but Melaith did not find him worthy,
for the reasons you had mentioned. After a short argument, the two got in
a fight, which made for the end of Bastahvilist. After his death, he came
to me and asked my aid in retrieving his axe. I did not wish to harm Sir
Melaith for any reason, so I declined. A friend Spirit Scholar went to
Melaith and requested the axe from him, later giving it to myself for
keeping. This was done to prevent physical harm from befalling the good
Sir Melaith *and* to prevent an untimely end for Bastahvilist, who has
always acted as a friend to Armaril.

I confronted Bastahvilist later about the incident, and asked him why he
did what he did and what he had learned from his experience. He gave me
his word to never bring blade to Sir Melaith again, and also promised
that if ever he loses the axe again he will not pursue violent means in
retrieving it.  Xor and I found this satisfactory, and since this 
compromise prevented bloodshed either from Sir Melaith or from 
Bastahvilist himself, we presented the axe to him once again.

Despite the fact that his people have had a hard time differentiating
Good and Evil since the Sundering, I do believe that Bastahvilist is
a kind soul, and that with proper guidance, he may even be worthy of
walking the halls of Armaril- a subject which he has inquired about to
Xor and myself more than once.


By showing mercy and kindness to all, Xor and I agree that this situation
is resolved. If you have any further questions, I'm open to speaking with
you on it.  Your concern is quite understandable, and I am heartened by it.

I look forward to seeing you again soon, Brachaormaul.
Pfusch.
~
